Dibble

Target IP: 192.168.156.110
Challenge Description: A good tool for making holes with. Careful you don't stick yourself!

Reconnaissance


Doing a port scan shows there are five TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. I performed an aggressive port scan against the open ports and obtained more information about the applications.

Enumeration

Port 3000: HTTP

Browsing to this port displays the web application above. I viewed the source-code of the web application, and I did not find anything useful.


However, I notice this application allows me to register an account. I created a new user using the credentials test:test.


I am able to view all the event logs. However, I am unable to create a new one as I am not an administrator user. The event log above mentions someone performed SQL injection and deleted the tables. Maybe I can perform SQL injection if I obtain the password of the user admin?

Port 27017: MongoDB

Since the target machine is running MongoDB, I connected to this application from my machine via mongo. There is an interesting database with the name account-app. This database has an interesting table called users. And this table contains the password hash ab6edb97f0c7a6455c57f94b7df73263e57113c85f38cd9b9470c8be8d6dd8ac of the user admin.


Previously, I created a user called test with the password test. This is shown in the previous image. I used the command db.users.updateOne({username: 'administrator'},{$set: {password: '8737729a3ada8674940065008dd87d9bc110221bf02b1048beab6078349e792c'}}) to change the password of the user administrator to test. This executed successfully!

Exploitation


After changing the password of the user administrator to test. I managed to successfully login to the web application as the user administrator, as shown above. However, I am still unable to modify the event logs!


I intercepted the POST request using Burpsuite, as shown above. There is an interesting header field called userLevel with the key ZGVmYXVsdA%3D%3D. I decoded this and obtained the word default.


Maybe I can put the base64-encoded administrator as the key? But still no luck. However, I tried admin and it worked! I used the base64-encoded key YWRtaW4=. In the image above, my new entry event was added.


I sent the message 10+232 to see if the code is executed, as the web application is using NodeJS.


And bingo! The new event log with the message 242 got appended. Maybe I can get it to execute a reverse shell connection?



Since the target machine is using NodeJS, I used the reverse shell code above. I tried a few different ports, and port 80 worked. I received a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 80, as shown above, with the session as benjamin.

Privilege Escalation


Running find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows the copy binary has SUID bit set, as shown above. I can use this binary to overwrite the /etc/passwd file. Using the command openssl passwd rooted, it generated the password hash MAiI/o21eXXVM.


Using the command echo 'super:MAiI/o21eXXVM:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash' | ./cp /dev/stdin "$LFILE", I created a root user called super with the password rooted as shown above. Then I switched to the new root user via su and password rooted. Now I have root access on the target machine, as shown above. I managed to overwrite everything inside the /etc/passwd file -- which is not good :')
